{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604598/1945092101/0055.xml":{"full_text":"Committee Debates\nMove to Summon\nElliott Roosevelt\nBULLETIN.\nDemocrats on the House\nWays and Means Committee j\ntoday voted down a proposal\nto question Elliott Roosevelt\npersonally about his business\naffairs.\nBy the Associated Press.\nSome House Ways and Means j\nCommittee members appeared ready\ntoday to press for personal appear\nances by Elliott Roosevelt and others\ninvolved in his financial affairs. j\nChairman Doughton called the\ncommittee to another closed door\nsession, hopeful of some decision on\nthe group's long inquiry into loans\nobtained by the late President\u2019s son.\nSome members indicated, however,\nthat they want young Roosevelt,\nJohn Hartford, president of the\nGreat Atlantic Pacific Tea Co.,\nand Jesse Jones, former Secretary\nof Commerce, to appear for ques\ntioning before any action is taken j\nby the committee.\nTax Legislation Pressing.\nOthers want to dispose of the in\nquiry today, so the committee can\nturn immediately to the writing of\nthe first peacetime legislation cut\nting taxes.\nThe inquiry began when reports\nwere published that Mr. Hartford,\nloaned Elliott $200,000 in 1939 in\nconnection with a Texas radio ven\nture. that Jesse Jones settled the\ndebt, for $4,000. and that Mr. Hart\nford listed the remaining $196,000 as\na bad debt deduction in his 1942 in\ncome tax return.\nThe committee has read almost\n1.000 pages of depositions submitted\nby Mr. Roosevelt. Mr. Hartford. Mr.\nJones and others. The question to\nbe determined is whether Mr. Hart\nford shall be allowed the bad debt\ndeduction. The Internal Revenue\nRurpaii thinks hp should\nTwo Avenues Appear Open.\nTwo possible avenues .appeared\nopen to the committee for disposi-;\ntion of the case:\n1. Agree with the bureau, and let\nMr. Hartford have the deduction.\n2. Recommend that the bureau\ndisallow the deduction, thereby\nt browing the whole thing into the\nUnited States Tax Court, if Mr\nHartford wishes to press his claim.\nIn either event it appeared cer\ntain the committee would transmit\na report to the House on the evi\ndence collected.\nSenate Due to Confirm\nD. C. Judges on Monday\nSenate action confirming Presi\ndent Truman's recent nominations\nto the Federal bench here was post\nponed until Monday when a wrangle\nover Undersecretary of State Dean\nAeheson, whose nomination also was\npending, unexpectedly broke in the\nSenate last night.\nAs a result, there was no executive\nsession of the Senate yesterday, j\nThis will come near the end of Mon\nday's session.\nWhen the time arrives, the Senate\nIs expected to give quick confirma\ntion to the nominations of E. Bar\nrett Prettyman of this city, Bennett\nChamp Clark, former Senator from\nMissouri, and Wilbur K. Miller of\nKentucky, to be associate justices\nof the United States Court of\nAppeals, and Alexander Holtzoff,\nexecutive assistant to Attorney Gen\neral Clark, to be an associate justice\nof District Court here.\nTwo New Infantile Cases\nReported in District Area\nTwo new- infantile paralysis cases\n\u25a0were reported yesterday by the\nHealth Department, bringing the\ntotal hospitalized in the District this\nyear to 178. At this time last year\nthere were 243 .cases in the Metro\npolitan Area.\nThe new cases are those of a 2\nyear-old boy from the 6500 block of\nRhode Island avenue in Prince\nGeorges County, Md., and a 4>2\nyear-old boy from the 1100 block of\nSouth Barton street, Arlington. Va.\nBoth cases are at Children's Hos\npital.\nA breakdown of Health Depart\nment figures shows 84 District cases\nand 94 out-of-town cases so far this\nyear, compared with 144 District\ncases and 99 out-of-town cases last\nyear.\nJobless\n'Continued From First Page.)\nof policy that would have to be\nfollowed by specific legislation when\na ever the President found that the\nbusiness outlook for an approaching\nyear would not provide jobs for all\navailable workers. The battle will\ncenter around conflicting schools of\nthought on the efficacy of public\nspending as a remedy for business\nripnrpssinnK.\nin the closing hours of Senate\ndebate on the temporary jobless aid\nbill administration forces won their\nonly floor fight by making the 26\nweek minimum duration of benefits\nmandatory. In other words, if a State\npays displaced workers $20 a week\nfor 20 weeks, the Federal Govern\nment will pay the same amount for\nsix additional weeks.\nAs the bill came from the Finance\nCommittee even the extension of\nduration was optional and required\na w'ritten request from each Gov\nernor.\nThe Senate upset another White\nHouse recommendation when it\ntacked on the bill a provision re\nturning the United States Employ\nment Service offices to the States\nin 90 days. The offices were bor\nrowed by the Federal Government\nfor recruiting war workers, and the\nadministration felt they should not\nbe returned in the midst of recon\nversion.\nAid to Government Workers.\nGovernment employes laid off be\ntween now and June, 1947, will be\npaid unemployment benefits out of\nFederal funds, but in accord with\nthe terms of the law\u2019 in the State\nin which they work. Here the Dis\ntrict law will govern. Senator Kil\ngore, Democrat, of West Virginia\ntried to have all Government per\nsonnel paid uniformly under the\nDistrict of Columbia law, but was\ndefeated.\nSenator McClellan, Democrat, of\nArkansas was beaten in two at\ntempts to eliminate or restrict the\npayment of travel expenses to war\nworkers to get to their homes or\nanother job.\nSome observers believe the House\ncommittee will whittle the admin\nistration program down still further\nby confining the bill to coverage for\nFederal employes. In that event,\nthe final terms would be written\nla conference.\na\nAID IN B-29 RAIDS\u2014This huge relief map of a section of Ja\npan is typical of many made in Hollywood for training films\nused to acquaint B-29 crews with targets on the Nipponese\nmainland. In this picture Capt. William G. Ryan, a navigator\nradar expert, checks details of the map.\n\u2014AP Wirephoto From Army Air Forces.\nMrs, Charles Warner,\nWife of Rector, Dies\nMrs. Elsie McOmber Warner, 70,\nwife of the Rev. Charles T. Warner, j\nD. D., rector of St. Alban\u2019s parish,!\ndied of leukemia last night in the1\nchurch rectory after a three-month\nillness. j\nA native of Saratoga Springs,\nN. Y\u201e Mrs. Warner came herej\nshortly before her marriage to Dr.\nWarner in 1912, the same year he\nwas installed as rector.\nMrs. Warner is survived by her\nhusband and a daughter, Mrs.\nConstance S. McElhinney, jr., wife\nof Ben McElhinney, 3209 Duke\nstreet. Alexandria, Va., and a\nbrother-in-law. Dr. John W. War\nner. 3409 Lowell street N.W.\nFuneral services will be held at\nSt. Alban's Church at 6 p.m. Sun\nday. Burial will take place at Dr.\nWarner\u2019s birthplace. Amherst, Va.\nPublisher Gives $100,000\nTo Form Peace Foundation\nBv the Associated press.\nTEXARKANA. Ark.-Tex.. Sept. 21.\n\u2014C. E. Palmer, Arkansas-Texas\nnewspaper publisher, announced to-!\nday the establishment of a $100,000 j\nfoundation to contribute to the \"true!\npeace for which we as a Nation)\nhave been striving.\u2019\u2019\nH. w. Stillwell, superintendent of\nthe Texarkana public schools, wull\nbe president of the fund, which will\nbe known as the Palmer Foundation.\nOne of the first projects of the\nfoundation will be to award prizes\nof $1,000 and $500 for the best pro\nposals which would answer this\nquestion: i\n\nuc>u inaj v\\ v. niv. uibd i/C ill\nyoung people a consciousness of,\nand a devotion to, the principles of'\nmorality that are embodied in the,\nGolden Rule\u2014\u2018Do unto others as you'\nwould have others do unto you?'\u201d\n\"This is an undertaking which I\nhope will contribute to the true\npeace for which we as a Nation have\nbeen striving,\u201d Mr. Palmer said. \"We\nhave learned by now that peace is\nnot something to be taken for\ngranted, but is a condition which\ncan be maintained only by the un\nselfish devotion of many millions\nof people.\u201d\nMr. Palmer, who was born in Spirit\nLake, Iowa, 69 years ago, has had\nan interest in Arkansas and North\neast Texas newspapers for 35 years.;\nFormer Liner Normandie\nDeclared Surplus by Navy\nEy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Sept. 21.\u2014The for\nmer French liner Normandie, now\ngathering moss and barnacles, has\nbeen declared surplus by the Navy.\nThe $60,000,000 former luxury ship\nwas swept by fire and partially cap\nsized in February. 1942. shortly after\nwork was begun to convert her into\na troopship to be known as the La\nfayette.\nThe Government spent nearly\n$14,000,000 trying to reclaim her.\nAfter an 18-month salvage job, she\nwas towed away and the Navy an\nnounced reconversion had been\ndropped.\nEdward V. Caywood, 75,\nTo Be Buried Tomorrow\nEdward V. Caywood, 75, retired\nGovernment employe and long-time\nresident of Bethesda, died Wednes\nday at his home, 4808 Battery lane,\nafter a long illness. Funeral services\nwill be held at 10:30 a.m. tomorrow\nat the Reuben Pumphrey funeral\nhome, Bethesda. Burial will be in\nRockville Union Cemetery.\nMr. Caywood is survived by his\nwidow, Mrs. Julia F. Caywood: two\ndaughters, Mrs. Howard Switzer,\nMiami, Fla., and Mrs. Vivian K.\nRobey, Bethesda: four grandchil\ndren and four great-grandchildren.\nHe was a native of Washington\nand had lived in the Bethesda\nneighborhood for 55 years. He retired\nseveral years ago after having been\nconnected with the Bureau of\nAnimal Industry, Agricultural De\npartment, for 36 years.\n\u201cPROBLEM\nHAIR\u201d\nmade\nr Lovely\nagain\nr\nADMIRACrON\nr\n\n1\nNational U. Law Alumni\nTo Honor Schweinhaut\nDistrict Court Justice Henry A.\nSchweinhaut will be honor guest at\na banquet to be given by the classes\nof 1923 and 1924 of National Uni\nversity Law School at 6:30 p.m. Sep\ntember 29 in the Continental Hotel.\nInvited guests include Attorney\nGeneral and Mrs. Clark, Chief Jus\ntice Bolitha J. Laws of District\nCourt, Chief Judge William Rich\nardson of the Municipal Court of\nAppeals, Chief Judge George P.\nBarse of Municipal Court, Judge El\nlen K. Raedy of Municipal Court,\nVictor S. Mersch, registrar of wills:\nUnited States Attorney Edward M.\nCurran. Corporation Counsel Rich\nmond B Keech and William Jasper\nStory, secretary of State for Mary\nland.\nMichael Lane and Louis Pearlstein,\nWashington attorneys, are arranging\nthe banquet. The toastmaster will\nbe Walter M. Bastian, chairman of\nthe Board of Trustees at National\nUniversity. George O'Connor is\nchairman of the Entertfrinment\nCommittee.\nSenate Group Approves\nPatterson, Symington\nEy the Associated Press.\nThe Senate Military Affairs Com\nmittee today unanimously approved\nthe nominations of Robert P. Pat\nterson as Secretary of War and W.\nStuart Symington as surplus prop\nerty administrator.\nCommittee action on the two key\nappointments will be reported to the\nSenate Monday, with confirmation\nexpected early in the week.\nMr. Symington will become the\nfirst single surplus property admin\nistrator. He formerly was chair\nman of the three-man board dis\nposing of wartime surpluses.\nDulles to I our turope\nFor Peace Treaty Data\nBy the Associated Puss.\nLONDON, Sept. 21.\u2014John Foster\nDulles has accepted a request from\nSecretary of State Byrnes to tour\nEurooean capitals and report on\nconditions that should figure in final\npeace settlements.\nMr. Dulles is expected to go to\nVienna. Warsaw, Berlin, Paris. Rome\nand perhaps Brussels and The Hague\nbut not to the Balkans or Moscow.\nMr. Dulles, adviser to Thomas E.\nDewey in the 1944 presidential cam\npaign, is now adviser to the Amer\nican delegation at the Council of\nForeign Ministers.\nPlaywright John Colton\nReported Critically III\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Sept. 21.\u2014John B.\nColton, playwright, is in a critical\ncondition at Metropolitan Hospital,\nwhere he was taken Tuesday after\ncollapsing, hospital officials said to\nday.\nMr. Colton is best known as co\nauthor w-ith Clemence Randolph of\nthe play \"Rain.\u201d Another of his\nplays was \"Shanghai Gesture.\u201d\nRussians Quit Teheran\nTEHERAN, Sept. 21 t/Pi.\u2014Foreign\nMinister Sepahbodi told the Iranian\nParliament today he was informed\nby the Soviet Ambassador that Rus\nsian forces had left Teheran yester\nday and that, in accordance with\ninstructions from Moscow, Russian\ncensorship here had been lifted.\nMussolini's Mistress\nReal Head of Regime,\nCountess Ciano Says\nthe Associat ed Presa.\nROME, Sept. 21.\u2014Countess Edda\nCiano says she still \"loved and\nmired\" her father, Benito Musso\nlini, even after he put to death her\nhusband, former Foreign Minister\nGaleazzo Ciano.\nShe denied she ever was the \"gay\neminence\" in Fascist politics and\nsaid she wanted to live the rest of\nher days on a small island \u201clike an\nordinary woman.\u201d\nThe countess was interviewed on\nLipari Island where she is interned\nby the Italian government after be-i\ning expelled from Switzerland.\n\u201cWhat I want most of all js that\nmy case be settled one way or the\nother,\u201d Countess Ciano said. \u201cThere;\nis nothing more unbearable than\nthis waiting without knowing.\u201d\nThose who know her say her lot\nis not so hard. She goes where she\npleases on the island, smokes Amer\nican cigarettes and has a superb\nview from her villa of the Mediter\nranean in which she swims occa\nsionally. Police in charge treat her;\nwith respect, always referring to her 1\nas countess, these Informants say. j\nExpected Better Than Lipari.\nThe countess wore light blue\nslacks, a flannel blouse and tennis\nsneakers when she met correspon\ndents in the parlor of her villa,\ni \"To tell the truth, I expected;\n.something better than Lipari,\u201d she\nsaid.\nCorrespondents observed she real\nly was in a very special position\nand she replied brusquely:\n\"I have always been in a very\nspecial position. In the end, it will\nbe in a very special position that I\nwill be shot\n\"It is my fate that I get the\nworst news suddenly like an unex- j\npected blow on the head. I was in\nSwitzerland and I turned the radio\nto the Milan station at exactly the\ninstant it was announced, \u2018At this\nmoment an enormous crowd is mov\ning toward the Piazza Loreto to\nview Mussolini's body\u2019.\u201d\nHated Duce's Mistress.\nShe said Claretta Petacci, Musso\nlini's mistress, who was slain with\nthe dictator, and whose body also\nwas exposed in the Piazza, had a\ngreat influence on her father.\n\"She became the true head of the\ngovernment,\u201d Countess Ciano said.\n\u201cI hated her because I saw where\nshe was dragging my father.\"\nShe asserted Mussolini \"intimate\nly hated the Germans,\" adding:\n\"But on the other hand, if he did\nnot go to war on their side, they\nwould have occupied us in one\nmonth, even if we fought well.\u201d\nThe countess said that \"after the\nexecution of my husband, I broke\nevery relation\" with Mussolini \"but,\nnevertheless, I loved and admired\nhim.\" She said she argued with\nher father frequently and \"per\nhaps I was the only person who did\nthat.\"\nRibbentrop Vicious Man.\n\"Hitler was more human than\ngenerally believed and he certainly\nhad charm,\u201d Edda said. \"The fero\ncious man was Ribbentrop (Joachim\nvon Ribbentrop, Nazi Foreign Min\nister awaiting trial as war crimi\nnal), even more than Himmler. He\nhated my husband because he knew\nhim to be anti-German and ready\nto deal with the Allies.\"\nAsked if she influenced Fascist\npolicy, the countess replied:\n\"I had the misfortune to be born'\nin politics, for which many things\nwere said about me. but 1 have1\nnever mixed up in politics.\u201d\nD. C. Girl Joins PCA\nMiss Janice O'Donnell, daughter\nof Mr. and Mrs. T. A. O'Donnell,\n5745 Thirteenth street N.W.. has re\nported for flight hostess training at\nPennsylvania Central Airlines. She\nattended Roosevelt High School and\nis a graduate of Cornell University.\nThe first union railway station in\nAmerica was built in Indianapolis.\n\nCOMMERCIAL\nARTIST\nWANTED\nIf you hove hod experience drawing\nfor retail stores and are interested l\nin working ior a newspaper, here is\njj a real opportunity. One qualified\ni to do furniture drawings preferred.\nWrite complete details including\nsalary expected to Wm. F. Schmick, Jr.\nBALTIMORESUNPAPERS\nBaltimore, Md.\nYou'll like this Salty Salt\ncomes plain or iodized. Ask foi\nSterling Salt today.\nEDDA CIANO.\nLaughlin Sues Biddle\nAnd Aides for Million\nClaiming malicious prosecution\nand interference with his civil\nrights, in connection with his prose\n:ution last year in Maryland on a\nrharge of impeding justice, James\nJ. Laughlin, attorney, filed suit in\nDistrict Court today asking $1,000.\n300 damages from former Attorney\nGeneral Biddle and others.\nMr. Laughlin was acquitted of the\n:harge last September. He was ac\ncused of introducing false testi\nmony and affiidavits in connection\nwith his defense of Hilliard Saun\nders, who had been convicted of\nparticipation in a $50,000 holdup of\ntwo bank messengers in Hyattsville\nin 1941.\nOther defendants named in the\nsuit filed today are Judge Samuel\nI. Rosenman, described as a confi\ndential assistant to the late Presi\ndent Roosevelt: O. John Rogge, Jus\ntice Department prosecutor in the\nsedition trial: James V. Bennett\ndirector of the Federal Bureau ol\nPrisons, and Joseph W. Sanford\nwarden of the Federal penitentiary\nin Atlanta.\nThe suit claims ^Mr. Laughlin'j\nprosecution was brought about, by\nthe defendants as a result of hif\nactivities as an attorney in the sedi\ntion trial. It charges the defendants\nknew the charges against Mr\nLaughlin to be erroneous and that\nthey attempted to deny him a fait\ntrial.\nStefan Advises Schools\nTo Modernize Curricula\nSchool officials were advised yes\nterday by Representative Stefan\nRepublican, of Nebraska to be sure\ntheir curricula were in step w'ith\nwartime scientific developments.\n\u201cDeVelopment and use of the\natomic bomb and the B-29S.\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cdid more to hasten the end\nof the war in the Pacific. They\ndemonstrated to school authorities\nthat more and more stress should\nbe placed on science and aeronautics\nin the education of our children.\u201d\nMr. Stefan, ranking minority\nmember of the House subcommittee\nwhich writes the annual District\nappropriation bills, voiced disap\npointment that school officials sc\nfar had been unable to carry out\nhis idea that the District schools\nacquire one or more surplus Army\nplanes for engineering laboratory\nuse by pupils.\nD. C. Girl Who Joined\nRival Sect Barred\nBy Adventist School\nA 14-year-old Washington girl has\nbeen forced to leave a Takoma Park\n(Md.l Seventh-Day Adventist school\nbecause she is a member of a rival\nreligious sect, officials of the school\nrevealed today.\nThe institution, the John Nevins\nAndrew School, is located at 117\nElm street. The girl, Dolores Pa\ntricia Herndon, 3314 Fifth street\nS.E., nov is registered at a public\nschool in Anacostia.\nAccording to William H. Hacket.\nvice chairman of the Adventist\nSchool Board, Dolores was asked to\nleave last Monday because she and\nher mother. Mrs. L. C. Herndon, are\nmembers of the Church of God\n(Seventh Dayi. School marks or\nconduct were not involved\u2019in the re\nquest, Mr. Hacket said.\nHe explained that Church of God\nmembers had been barred from at\ntending Adventist schools because\nof a \u201cdisturbance\u201d last year when\nsome literature attacking Adventist\nbeliefs were distributed by members\nof the rival sect.\nAlthough admitting that other\ni non-Adventist students are attend\ning the school. Mr. Hacket pointed\ni out that no denominational diffi\nculties had ever arisen between them\nand the Adventists.\nMrs. Herndon, who withdrew' from\nthe Seventh-Day Adventists last\nspring, said no questions had arisen\nat that time concerning her daugh\nter's attendance at the school.\nShe said a notice had been re\nceived from tlie school before it\ni opened this fall advising them of\nthe start, of the school term and\nthat she had taken it as an indica\ntion Dolores would be welcomed as\na student.\nHer daughter was registered Sep\ntember 11 and her tuition paid for\nthe first month, Mrs. Herndon as\nserted. She added that Dolores at\ntended the school all last week and\nMonday morning before she was\nasked to leave. Mrs. Herndon also\nexpressed the \u201chighest respect\u201d for\nthe school and those connected\nwith it.\nI\nTrain to be an\nOil Burner\nEngineer\nGood wages while learning.\nClasses Begin Oct. 1st\nInstructions in oil combus\ntion. automatic electric\ncontrol, oil heating, instal\nlation and burner assembly.\nLimited classes, place your\napplication at once.\nExcellent pay guaranteed\ngraduates. For application\ncall\nMR. ROBESON,\nChief Engineer\nColumbia Specialty\nCo. Inc.\nWisconsin 7700\ni\nBenning Power Plant's\nWarehouse Hit by Fire\nA fire yesterday afternoon in a\none-story warehouse of the Potomac\nElectric Power Co. plant at Thirty\nfourth street and Benning road N.E.\ncaused only minor damage, police\nreported today. Two alarms were\nsounded.\nAn overheated creosotp vat caused\nthe fire, which burned for three\nhours. It was prevented from\nspreading to the main power plant\n200 feet away. No one was injured.\nM. Koenigsberg Dies;\nHears! Executive\nEr ihe Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Sept, 21.\u2014Moses\nKoenigsberg, 67, retired Hearst news\npaper executive who formerly was\npresident of King Features Syndi\ncate. International News Service and\nUniversal News Service, died today\nof a heart attack at his home.\nWhen he left the Hearst organiza\ntion in 1928 he also held the presi\ndency of Star Adcraft Service, Cos\nmopolitan News Service, and Pre\nmier Syndicate and was vice presi\ndent and general manager of the\nInternational Feature Service.\nMr. Koenigsberg, born in New' Or\nleans, began his newspaper career\nat 9 when he wrote and set in type\nhis own newspaper. A $100 essay\nprize which he won led to the offer\nof a reporter\u2019s job on thp San An\ntonio Times when he was 13. That\nsame year he became editor of the\npaper and at 16 he w'as publisher of\nthe Sar Antonio Evening Star.\nBy the time he was 25, he war\nmanaging editor of the Chicago\nAmerican. He was a Spanish-Ameri\ncan W\u2019ar veteran.\nA. J. Hamilton, Laundry\nGeneral Manager, Dies\nAndrew J. Hamilton. 48. general\nmanager of the Morningside Laun\ndry, Silver Spring, for the last 10\nyears, died today at the Washington\nSanitarium, Takoma Park, after an\nillness of several weeks.\nA native of Rutherford. N. J., Mr.\nHamilton lived at 1941 Capitol View\navenue, Capitol View, Md. He was\na past preisdent of Silver Spring\nRotary Club and was active in the\nSilver Spring Board of Trade and\nthe Izaak Walton League of Silver\nSpring.\nBesides his widow. Mrs. Mary\nEmma Hamilton, he is survived by\na sister, Mrs. May Michaels, and\ntwo brothers, Roy aftd Eddie Hamil\nton. all of New Jersey.\nFuneral services will be held at 3\np.m. tomorrow at the Warner E.\nPumphrey funeral home, 8434\nGeorgia avenue. Silver Spring.\nBurial will be in Fort Lincoln\nCemetery.\nAND ALL APPLIANCES FOR\nI'm not eating this cheese without\nPetri Wine a\nI fAi.roon\nPetri Took Time To Bring You Good Wine\n6 1941, P**rt Wtai Wn rrtMcitc*, Ce*H.\nVoin\u2019ituriik Piedelt\non Ute Soda Te\nHauling mile-long freights over the\nsteep mountain grades calls for\ni plenty of head-end power.\nSanta Fe is providing a lot of that\npower with the greatest fleet of\n5400 horse-power Diesel locomo\ntives in American railroading.\n80 of these blue and yellow giant\n\"head-ends\u201d the most powerful\nfreight Diesels in the \u2022world\u2014are\nnow' in operation on the Santa Fe.\nThis dieselization program is one\nof many important steps by Santa\nFe in providing the most modern\nfreight equipment for the peacetime\ntransportation needs of America's\nWest and Southw est. j\nof the big fleet of Santa Fe\nfreight Diesels at a service base.\ni^B\\_ /fl\n^^B&^ B\nSANTA FE SYSTEM LINES\nReady in War\u2014Ready for Peace\nC. BATHAM. Goner*! Agent\nH. N. ECCLESTON. Dist. Pass. Agt .sANTA FE RY.\n\u202233 Shoroham Bldg., WASHINGTON 8, D. C., Phonos: Di.tnct 7984-\u00bb\n\u2022Copyright ]fW, Lea PeW, tee., llV YHfc M* Yf Heed by permieetoe. I4UA\ni >-i e\\","height":"31728","width":"22432"}}
